I think someone asked balloons to give a TL;DR of his article and so I thought I'd start with one.

Bzzzzzzzzzzzzzzzzzt! Bama, sweetheart, what was that? IT WAS BAD! It had nothing! No fire, no energy, no nothin'! You know I have a show to run here, you know? Hmm? Hmm? And it must pop, Pop, POP! So next week from 2:30 to 6:00, will you please act like you have more than a two word vo-cab-uh-lary? It must be green, OK? OK?

I guess I'll start with the SR by Drive graph. We never broke 0.6 on any drive and the closest was on the first drive where our SR was 0.57 and that drive ended in a interception! Our mean SR on all of our drives was 0.286. This is the first season that I've calculated this mean, but I don't think we need to compare this number to any other game to know that's just bad. (Partly self NOTE: make turnover drives a black/something bar).

I'm not sure how to interpret this other than it was better than ours (approximately 40% to our 29%).

At first the SR by Distance to 1st/TD looks great at the 1-3 yard distance until you realize that we were only on this range twice during the game! Of our basically non-kicking offensive plays, 41 out of a total of 62 offensive plays were in the 10-12 interval. And 5 were 13 yards or longer.


If we look at the Yards to Success vs Yards gained by Down and its associated table it's just more yuck. A mean distance of 10 is of course normal on first down and the distance standard deviation of 0 would indicate that we didn't commit any penalties on 1st down nor did Texas. A mean gain of 5.78 looks like a great number since 1st down success from 10 yards is 5 yards, but the standard deviation of 8.19 yards means that I am now interested in the median... Sorry for the delay, but I had to add some code to calculate the median gained. And that's not good. On 1st down we had a median gain of 3 yards which is 2 yards short of the 5 to be successful. (Another self NOTE: Might be time to see how to make a box-and-whisker plot.) Our mean/median distance to a 1st/TD just gets worse on 2nd and 3rd downs (9.05/10, 9.5/9). But hey, on the one time we went for it on 4th we only had to go 3 yards and gained 6, so there's that. Lets dig a little deeper into the Distance by Downs.

(Note that for the SR-1st-Downs graph the colors are not meaningful other than they are supposed to help distinguish the bars.) It's a little hard to see exactly what the Yards-Success-Gained is telling us for 1st down, but the SR-1st-Downs shows that we only had a SR of .41 with 27 plays. Second down looks bad in both graphs. Looking at Yards-Success-Gained there are way too many red dots vs green. And the SR-1st-Downs backs that up since we had:
